@baseUrl = https://localhost:60711

# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Synthetic data test suite — SMOTENCGenerator behind /api/Synthetic/Generate
#
# Generator facts that shape these tests (see SyntheticController.cs):
#   • SMOTE-NC fitted ONCE per process (Seed=42, K=5) on 50 hardcoded customer
#     rows: Age, Income, Education (categorical 0–3), CreditScore.
#   • SMOTE interpolates between a seed row and one of its K nearest neighbors —
#     it can only generate INSIDE the convex hull of the seed data. No value can
#     ever fall outside the seed min/max. Strength: no garbage rows (unlike the
#     CTGAN attempt, which produced negative incomes). Weakness: zero novelty —
#     every synthetic row is a blend of two real rows (a privacy consideration).
#   • Education is interpolated NC-style: the categorical column snaps to a real
#     category index, so values must be EXACTLY 0/1/2/3 — never 1.0000003.
#   • The seed data is strongly correlated by construction
#     (Age~Income ≈ 0.99, Age~CreditScore ≈ 0.95, Income~CreditScore ≈ 0.97) —
#     correlation preservation is the headline fidelity metric in the response.
#   • Request contract: numSamples is OPTIONAL (default 20) and silently CLAMPED
#     to [1, 200] — out-of-range values are corrected, not rejected. The only
#     400s come from model binding (wrong JSON type / empty body).
#   • Seed bounds for reference: Age [21,60], Income [26000,130000],
#     Education [0,3], CreditScore [550,820].
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


### 1. Smoke test — empty body, default sample count
# The request record has numSamples as nullable; omitting it exercises the
# documented default.
# EXPECTED (verified): 200 OK with exactly 20 rows; modelInfo.generatedSamples
#           = 20. trainMs ≈ 1.2 s on the FIRST call of the process — not the
#           SMOTE fit itself (which has no training loop; the epochs argument is
#           unused) but one-time assembly load + JIT riding on the lazy init.
#           inferenceMs ≈ 9 ms; subsequent requests pay generation cost only.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
}


### 2. Quick eyeball batch — 5 samples for manual row inspection
# Small enough to read every row. Each row should LOOK like a plausible customer:
# Age/Income/CreditScore jointly consistent (young → low income → low score,
# senior → high income → high score), because each row is a blend of two real
# neighbors that already obey that pattern.
# EXPECTED (verified): 5 rows, each with Age in [21,60], Income in
#           [26000,130000], Education exactly one of 0/1/2/3, CreditScore in
#           [550,820], and no implausible combination (e.g. Age 22 with Income
#           120000 cannot occur — the seed data contains no such neighbors to
#           blend). Sample row from a real run: [54.31, 118904.30, 3, 800.33] —
#           a plausible senior PhD profile.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "numSamples": 5
}


### 3. CHALLENGE — statistical fidelity audit at max scale (200 samples)
# 200 synthetic rows from 50 seeds (4× oversampling) — the realistic "augment my
# training set" use case. With n=200 the sampling noise is small enough for the
# response's realStats/syntheticStats/correlations to be a meaningful audit.
# EXPECTED (verified, n=200): synthetic mean/std within ~1% of real —
#           Age 38.4 vs 38.2 (std 10.85 vs 11.06), Income 73.3k vs 72.5k
#           (std 31.1k vs 31.7k), CreditScore 709 vs 707 (std 82.3 vs 82.1).
#           Age/Income std land slightly BELOW real — interpolation shrinks
#           variance toward the cluster interior, the known SMOTE bias.
#           ALL SIX pairwise correlations within 0.01 of real (e.g. Age~Income
#           0.9884 vs 0.9893, Income~CreditScore 0.9712 vs 0.9681). This is the
#           property that made SMOTENC win over CTGAN (diverged) and Copula
#           (correlations degraded to 0.82–0.93) on this seed set.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "numSamples": 200
}


### 4. CHALLENGE — boundary + privacy audit (200 samples, different lens)
# Same request as test 3 but verify three structural properties of the ROWS:
#   a) CONVEX HULL: every value within seed min/max (Age [21,60], Income
#      [26000,130000], CreditScore [550,820]) — SMOTE cannot extrapolate, so a
#      single out-of-range value would be a library bug, not noise.
#   b) CATEGORICAL INTEGRITY: every Education value is EXACTLY 0, 1, 2 or 3 —
#      float noise here would mean the schema's categorical flag was ignored
#      (the failure mode of the Copula generator).
#   c) PRIVACY: count rows identical to a seed row. SMOTE's gap factor λ ∈ [0,1]
#      can land on/near an endpoint, reproducing a real customer record exactly —
#      worth measuring before calling synthetic data "anonymized".
# EXPECTED (verified, 200 rows): (a) ZERO hull violations — every value inside
#           the seed bounds; (b) ZERO non-integer Education values (distinct
#           values exactly {0,1,2,3}); (c) ZERO exact seed-row duplicates — the
#           gap factor λ stayed strictly inside (0,1) in this run. Do NOT read
#           (c) as "privacy-safe": every synthetic row still lies on the line
#           segment between two real customer records, so attribute disclosure
#           via linkage remains possible even without exact copies.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "numSamples": 200
}


### 5. CHALLENGE — degenerate single sample (statistics edge case)
# numSamples = 1: syntheticStats are computed over ONE row (std must be 0) and
# Pearson correlation is undefined for n=1 (zero variance ⇒ denominator 0).
# EXPECTED (verified): 200 OK, exactly 1 row. syntheticStats: min = max = mean
#           (the row itself), std = 0 for all four columns. All six
#           correlations[].synthetic = 0 — the implementation returns 0 when the
#           denominator vanishes, so a reader must NOT interpret 0 here as
#           "no correlation"; it means "undefined".
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "numSamples": 1
}


### 6. CHALLENGE — RNG advance across calls (send this request TWICE)
# Seed=42 makes the generator deterministic per PROCESS, but Generate advances
# the internal RNG state, and the singleton facade shares one generator across
# requests.
# EXPECTED (verified): two consecutive sends of this identical request return
#           completely DIFFERENT rows (the second call continues the RNG stream —
#           no caching, no reset). Restarting the API and replaying the same
#           request sequence reproduces the same rows again (Seed=42).
#           Determinism is per process-lifetime sequence, not per request.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "numSamples": 3
}


### 7. Clamping — zero and negative sample counts are corrected, not rejected
# numSamples = -5 is invalid input, but the controller clamps to the [1,200]
# floor instead of returning 400.
# EXPECTED (verified): 200 OK with exactly 1 row, modelInfo.generatedSamples = 1.
#           Note for API consumers: you cannot distinguish "I asked for 1" from
#           "my invalid count was silently corrected" — a deliberate POC
#           trade-off.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "numSamples": -5
}


### 8. Clamping — absurdly large request is capped at 200
# numSamples = 100000 would be a 100k-row generation (and an easy DoS vector);
# the controller caps at 200.
# EXPECTED (verified): 200 OK with exactly 200 rows, modelInfo.generatedSamples
#           = 200 — no error, no warning. The response itself (generatedSamples)
#           is the only signal the cap was applied.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "numSamples": 100000
}


### 9. Validation — wrong JSON type for numSamples
# "twenty" cannot bind to int?.
# EXPECTED (verified): 400 Bad Request from MODEL BINDING — RFC 9110
#           ValidationProblemDetails with errors["$.numSamples"] ("The JSON
#           value could not be converted…") plus a generic errors["request"]
#           entry. The action never runs. This and test 10 are the only ways
#           this endpoint says 400.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "numSamples": "twenty"
}


### 10. Validation — completely empty request body
# No JSON at all (Content-Length: 0). [ApiController] requires a body for
# [FromBody] parameters.
# EXPECTED (verified): 400 Bad Request — ValidationProblemDetails with
#           "A non-empty request body is required." Contrast with test 1, where
#           an empty OBJECT `{}` is valid and yields the default 20 rows.
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/Synthetic/Generate
Content-Type: application/json
